    "body": "**Initial problem**\r\nConverting an array of `char *` into a python `list` of `bytes` seems to be only implemented when the array size is a constant.\r\n```cython\r\ncdef extern char *array_static[10]\r\ndef foo():\r\n    return array_static\r\n```\r\nWhich produce C code like this.\r\n```c\r\n__pyx_t_1 = __Pyx_carray_to_py_char___2a_(array_static, 10); \r\n```\r\n\r\nBut it is not supported when the array size is dynamic. (Of course, cython has no way of knowing the array size.)\r\n```cython\r\ncdef extern char **array_dynamic\r\ndef foo():\r\n    return array_dynamic\r\n```\r\n\r\nBut the array size doesn't have to be a known constant for the automatic conversion to take place. For instance in this case.\r\n```cython\r\ncdef extern const int asize\r\ncdef extern char *myarray[asize]\r\ndef foo():\r\n    return myarray\r\n```\r\nWhich produces.\r\n```c\r\n__pyx_t_1 = __Pyx_carray_to_py_char___2a_(myarray, asize);\r\n```\r\n\r\nI guess there would be a way to trick cython into thinking the array size is a constant when it's actually a variable. And I could modify that variable in the function `foo`. But that'd be a pretty ugly solution.\r\n\r\n**Solution I'd like**\r\nIt is already possible to convert a `char *` to a `bytes` object when its length is already known by using the slice notation.\r\n```cython\r\ncdef extern char *s\r\ndef foo():\r\n    return s\r\ndef bar():\r\n    return s[:42]\r\n```\r\nWhere `foo` is compiled using `__Pyx_PyBytes_FromString(s)` while `bar` uses `__Pyx_PyBytes_FromStringAndSize(s + 0, 42 - 0)`.\r\n\r\nSo I'd suggest using the same notation to make the array size known to cython and be able to use the automatic conversion to `list` of `bytes`.\r\n\r\n```cython\r\ncdef extern char **array_dynamic\r\ndef foo():\r\n    cdef int size = 42\r\n    return array_dynamic[:size]\r\n```\r\n\r\n**Alternatives**\r\nThe workarounds are quite obvious. Like building the list item by item, using the automatic `char *` to `bytes` conversion on each element. Or using the CPython C API; Basically reimplmementing some functions from `Utility/CConvert.pyx`.\r\n",
